When my local party’s Momentum activists voted to censor me, it didn’t surprise me.
After all, I am the last in a series of British parliamentarians who have been told that we are not welcome, all to say what we think.
My parliamentary colleague Joan Ryan received a similar treatment because he manifested himself with determination against anti-Semitism.
In my case, with the motion of censure I was criticized for disagreeing with Jeremy Corbyn.
On the importance of a responsible economic policy, on national security, on Europe. Ironically, these are similar issues with respect to which Jeremy disagreed with previous leaders.
In the notice of the meeting on Friday of the Nottingham Labour Party it was reported that "we want meetings to be inclusive and productive".
For most of my eight years as a local MP, the meetings of the General Committee held on Friday night have been exactly that way.
Unfortunately, this is not the tone of many meetings, and the promise of "more generous and kinder" policies has long been forgotten, if it ever existed.
It is becoming increasingly clear that divergent opinions are not tolerated by the Labour Party, and each opinion is judged on the basis of whether it is acceptable for the party leadership.
This began shortly after Jeremy became the leader, as colleagues with whom he previously thought he shared a similar political vision expected me to turn 180 degrees and take positions that I would never have taken, whether on national security or on the EU single market.
Whenever I speak in public, whatever I say, social networks are filled with aggressive messages in which an appeal is made so that my candidacy is not renewed, center policies are denounced and I am told that I should not be in the Labour Party.
And that doesn’t just happen to me.
In fact, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, since the messages I receive are usually political.
I’m impressed by the professionalism and determination of colleagues who have to deal with a torrent of sexist and racist attacks every day, and they don’t get ragged.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this political era is to see how the level of abuse has been normalized.
Jeremy Corbyn declared last week that the Labour Party should foster a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that diverse party, and with each motion of "no confidence" or each change in the rules of selection, the party narrows more.
In the last two years I have received a lot of advice and I have been advised to keep my head low, that it was not so expressive and "everything would be fine".
But I didn’t get into politics for that.
Since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago, in my time as a student, stimulated by Thatcher's negligent government, which left all my class literally sunk, I have tried to defend better public services for those who need it most, whether as a local adviser or as a government minister.
I have never hidden my politics, not even in the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could in any way doubt about my political positions and points of disagreement with the current leadership.
To those who promoted the motion on Friday, I would tell them that at a time when the country is heading towards a Brexit that will harm homes, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But, in reality, the message I want to convey is not directed towards Nottingham Momentum, but towards my constituents, whether they are Labour members or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise you that no threat of non-renewal of my candidacy or any political interest will prevent it from acting, in my opinion, for the benefit of the interests of all of you.
