John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
Independent schools in Scotland have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is enhanced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, for the career they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we observe that modern languages remain a very popular and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you will reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will come to his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that languages lead the classification tables with the highest qualifications in independent schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained the upper A grade.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of students obtained a higher A rating in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A rating.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as a subject of choice, are kept in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in curricula from independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Competency Commission revealed that of the reasons employers gave to the fact that they found it difficult to fill vacancies, 17% were attributed to the lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
Since more and more potential job opportunities require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that a person chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competence like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% did not know how to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find an important job.
In Scotland there is diversity among schools in terms of the languages taught.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be more important for the UK for the future, by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, you can always choose between a series of languages in independent schools, which have teaching staff specialized in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
In the global commercial environment of the current era, it cannot be denied that languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
