North Korea declares that it will not unilaterally disarm "in any way" if no signs of trust are appreciated
The North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were intensifying his distrust of the United States and that, under such circumstances, the country would not unilaterally eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" during the previous year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test center, and committing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
However, we do not observe any response in consonance with the U.S.," he said.
Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and in such circumstances we will not unilaterally initiate disarmament.
While Ri resumed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phase-based" denuclearization approach by which North Korea would be rewarded as you took measures gradually, his statements seemed significant because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization fully, as Pyongyang had already done in the past.
Ri referred to Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump's joint statement at the first summit between a U.S. acting president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has attempted to formally end the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has previously announced that Pyongyang must eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted the call to relax the harsh international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
The U.S. insists that denuclearization must first occur and the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, in addition to opposing the "end-of-war declaration," Ri said.
The perception that sanctions will make us kneel is a chimera of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are intensifying our distrust.”
Ri did not refer to plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: "If the party involved in the matter of denuclearization were South Korea instead of the U.S., denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have reached this stagnation situation."
However, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from what he held last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting the U.S. territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after President Trump called Kim "Rocket Man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but stated that much remains to be done and sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
Last Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for this and that “it doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
