Harvard students take a course on resting habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of studying throughout the night, stimulated by caffeine.
An academic observed that students at the world's number one university are often clueless about what it's like to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk on the impact that sleep deprivation had on learning.
At the end of the talk, a girl approached me and said, “Why do you tell me all this now in my last year?”
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
In the course, implemented for the first time this year, students are explained the basics about how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, as well as general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's health services, stated that the University decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, how it affects sports performance to lack of sleep, and the importance of maintaining a sleeping routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Below, a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the effects it has on health smoking cigarettes," Czeisler said.
The culture of pride in staying up all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure that students suffer make sleep deprivation an increasing problem.
Making sure to enjoy good quality sleep for long enough should be a "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask postgraduate students to undertake a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students take into account the fact of putting an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
