In Palu, more than 16,000 people have been evacuated after the disaster.
Below are some important facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Celebes:
Palu is the capital of Central Celebes Province, located at the end of a narrow bay on the western coast of Celebes Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a regency that stretches along more than 300 km of coastline to the northwest of the island of Celebes.
The regency, an administrative region lower than a province, had a population of approximately 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and agriculture are the pillars of the economy of the Central Celebes province, especially in the Donggala coastal region.
The exploitation of nickel mines is also important in the province, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the coast at the other end of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have suffered several tsunamis in the last 100 years, according to Indonesia's disaster mitigation agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami occurred west of Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Ring of Fire and earthquakes often occur there.
Below are the main earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On 26 December, a major earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Ace in northern Sumatra caused a tsunami that hit 14 countries and killed 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Thousands of people died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: An earthquake of magnitude 6.8 hit southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, causing a tsunami that destroyed the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.6 shook an area of pop from the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.5 shook one of the islands of Mentawai off the Sumatran coast, causing a tsunami of up to 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A mild earthquake affected the regency of Pidie Jaya in Aceh and caused destruction and panic, as the population recalled the devastation of the 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, no tsunami occurred, but more than 100 people died from the buildings that fell.
2018: A series of major earthquakes occurred on the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok that killed more than 500 people, mainly in the north of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily trapped.
